"Mobile crowdsensing enables a crowd of individuals to cooperatively collect and share information with customers with common interest using their mobile devices. The success of mobile crowdsensing strongly depends on the participating mobile users. The broader participation, the more sensing reports are collected; on the other hand, the more replicate data may be generated, which brings heavy communication overhead. Data deduplication can improve communication efficiency, but meanwhile disclose the sensing data. In this paper, we propose a fog-assisted mobile crowdsensing framework that enables fog nodes to allocate tasks based on user mobility for improving the accuracy of task assignment, and a fog-assisted secure data deduplication scheme (Fo-SDD) to improve communication efficiency while maintaining high data confidentiality. Specifically, a BLS-oblivious pseudo-random function is designed to enable fog nodes to detect and delete the replicate data in sensing reports without exposing the content of reports, except the equality of the underlying sensing data. To further prevent privacy leakage of mobile users, we extend the Fo-SDD to hide the identities of mobile users in data collection. Chameleon hash function is leveraged to achieve contribution claim and reward retrieval for anonymous mobile users. Finally, we demonstrate that both schemes achieve secure data deduplication with low computational and communication overhead."
